<p></p><div id="attachment_223108" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="max-width: 310px;"><img class="wp-image-223108 size-medium" src="https://cdn.ps.emap.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/10/MG_6961-1-300x194.png" alt="Professor Anandi Ramamurthy" width="300" height="194"><p class="wp-caption-text">Professor Anandi Ramamurthy</p></div>
<p>"Using creative storytelling we aim to deepen the societal understanding of the critical contribution that BME nurses and care workers have made to the NHS and social care, both historically and today," she said.</p>
<p>“The stories of BME nursing staff and the pandemic are entwined with complex histories of racism which can only be fully understood through amplifying the experiences and voices of those who have been marginalised.</p>
<p>“We hope to develop our understanding of what went wrong in our response to the pandemic and consider what lessons we can learn to create a more equitable society and an NHS that is able to deliver the best patient care.”</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Ken Fero, UK documentary filmmaker and co-founder of Migrant Media, said he hoped the documentary would inspire “significant change”.</p>
<p>"It is important that those who have been on the Covid-19 frontline – so many of whom have been from Black and migrant backgrounds – have their experiences documented and their hopes for the future heard," he added.</p><div style="text-align: center; " class="nursi-inread-slot-2" data-id="206101" id="nursi-1759287732">
